[[File:Spoleto. Santuario della Madonna di Loreto.jpg|thumb|Church of Madonna di Loreto in Spoleto]] '''Annibale Lippi''' (16th century-Rome, after 18 November 1581) was an Italian architect active during the second half of 16th century.<ref name=erc>{{cite web|last1=Ercolino|first1=Maria Grazia|title=Lippi, Annibale|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/annibale-lippi_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|website=www.treccani.it|publisher=Treccani|accessdate=6 July 2015|language=Italian|location=Rome|date=2005}}</ref> He was son of the sculptor and architect [[Nanni di Baccio Bigio]]. Pupil of [[Francesco de' Rossi|Francesco Salviati]], his only certain works are the church of Our Lady of Loreto at [[Spoleto]], built around 1572, where he adopts a Vignola style, the churches of Santa Maria a Monte Cavallo and Santa Maria della Pietà a Piazza Colonna, both in Rome.<ref name=erc/> The [[Villa Medici]] in Rome, who used to be assigned to it, is probably due to his father, but he worked there during the construction.<ref name=erc/> In Rome Lippi restored the [[Palazzo dei Convertendi]] at Piazza Scossacavalli in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]], when this was bought by Cardinal [[Giovanni Francesco Commendone|Francesco Commendone]] (1523–84), and gave to the building its definitive facade.<ref name=gi48>Gigli (1992) p. 48</ref> In 1578 he appeared among the members of the [[Pontifical Academy of Fine Arts and Letters of the Virtuosi al Pantheon|Accademia dei Virtuosi at Pantheon]].<ref name=erc/> He died after 18 November 1581 when, already ill, wrote his testament, and was buried in the family tomb in [[Trinità dei Monti]] in Rome.<ref name=erc/>
