{{Infobox person | name = Janet Baus | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth --> | death_place = | othername = | occupation = film director, producer and editor | yearsactive = | spouse = | domesticpartner = | website = }} '''Janet Baus''' is a documentary film and television director, producer and editor. In 1993, she co-directed ''[[Lesbian Avengers Eat Fire Too]]'' with [[Su Friedrich]], about activist group the [[Lesbian Avengers]].<ref>{{Cite book | last = Blaetz | first = Robin | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Women's experimental cinema: critical frameworks | publisher = [[Duke University Press]] | year = 2007 | location = | pages = 317 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=e8Wj-XgOMdAC&pg=PA317 | doi = | id = | isbn =0-8223-4044-5 }} </ref> In 2003 she produced [[John Scagliotti]]'s film ''[[Dangerous Living: Coming Out in the Developing World]]'' about gay and lesbian people in non-Western countries. She had worked with Scagliotti before, having a co-producer credit on his 1999 film ''[[After Stonewall]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Filmmakers |work= |publisher=Official After Stonewall Productions site |year=2003 |url=http://www.afterstonewall.com/1/dl_filmmakers.html |doi= |accessdate=February 7, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221025047/http://www.afterstonewall.com/1/dl_filmmakers.html |archivedate=February 21, 2010 |df= }} </ref> Her 2006 film ''[[Cruel and Unusual (2006 film)|Cruel and Unusual]]'', co-directed with [[Dan Hunt (film director)|Dan Hunt]] and [[Reid Williams]], was a documentary about pre-operative male-female transsexual women in men's prisons.<ref name=chronicle>{{Citation | title = 'The Gymnast' wins best feature at LGBT film festival | newspaper = [[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date = June 28, 2006 | url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/06/28/DDGKOJKSKI1.DTL | accessdate =February 7, 2010 }} </ref> It won the Michael J. Berg Documentary Award at the 2006 [[Frameline Film Festival]] and the Freedom Award at [[L.A. Outfest]].<ref name=chronicle /><ref>{{Cite web | title = Janet Baus&nbsp;— Awards | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | url = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0062460/awards | accessdate =February 7, 2010 }} </ref> Baus has also won the [[Cine Golden Eagle]], the [[Vito Russo Award]], the [[Chicago International Television Award]] and the [[Gold Aurora Award]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Janet Baus | publisher = [[Women Make Movies]] | url = http://www.wmm.com/filmCatalog/makers/fm396.shtml | accessdate =February 7, 2010 }} </ref>
