{{Infobox Artwork | image_file= 1502 Raffael Madonna Solly anagoria.JPG | title=Madonna Solly | artist=[[Raphael]] | year=1500–1504 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on wood]] | height_metric=52 | width_metric=38 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Berlin]] | museum=[[Gemäldegalerie, Berlin|Gemäldegalerie]] }}
The '''''Solly Madonna''''' by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[renaissance]] artist [[Raphael]] was painted somewhere between 1500 and 1504.
An early work, it clearly shows the influence of Raphael's teacher [[Perugino]].<ref name="Sociology, Religion and Grace">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pEh_AgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA267&dq=%22Solly%20Madonna%22&pg=PA267#v=onepage&q=%22Solly%20Madonna%22&f=false | title=Sociology, Religion and Grace | publisher=Routledge | author=Szakolczai, Arpad | year=2007 | isbn=9781134194506}}</ref> Two motifs in this work would recur in later Madonnas by Raphael. The virgin Mary is reading a book, as in the [[Madonna and Child (Raphael, Pasadena)|Madonna and Child]] in the [[Norton Simon Museum]], the [[Connestabile Madonna]], the [[Madonna Colonna]] and the [[Madonna del cardellino]]. As in that last painting a small bird, a [[European goldfinch|goldfinch]], is part of the scene.<ref name="Uffizi">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oNE3ofu8psMC&lpg=PA420&dq=%22Solly%20Madonna%22&pg=PA420#v=onepage&q=%22Solly%20Madonna%22&f=false | title=Uffizi | publisher=Giunti Editore | author=Fossi, Gloria | year=2004 | isbn=9788809036765}}</ref>
The painting is located in the [[Gemäldegalerie, Berlin]]. It is called the ''Solly Madonna'' because it was owned by the British banker and art collector [[Edward Solly]] (1776–1848).
